title: The thick-target 9Be(d,n) neutron spectra for deuteron energies between 2.6 and 7.0 MeV

x4freetext: Experiment performed at the Argonne
Tandem Dynamitron Accelerator
Beryllium metal target with thickness of 0.75 mm
and diameter of 25.4 mm mounted in a cooper block.
The thickness of the cooper behind the Be disk was
Low-mass, three-electrode ionization chamber
with an electrode separation of 0.6 cm, and with the
outer electrodes at ground potential. The center
electrode is biased at + 400 V and supplies the
signal.The detector was operated as a flow chamber,
using high-purity methane at one atmosphere.
The three electrodes are formed from four platinum
disks, 70 mm dia. by 0.13 mm thick, with uranium
oxide U(3)O(8) deposits on one side. The disks are
arranged so there are U(3)O(8) deposits on the four-
interior electrode surfaces for a total thickness of
~ 2 mg U/cm2. Deposits are either 235U or 238U
(natural uranium). Time resolution of the fission
detector was approx. 3 ns.
Neutron energy was determined by time of flight
on the flight path of 2.6 - 6.75 m. Deuteron beam
pulses 20 - 30 ns wide were bunched by double
klystron buncher to produce pulse width of < 2 ns
at the Be target
Compiled by S.H.

x4headers.headerHelp: Angle, laboratory system

x4freetext: Data taken from tab. A -I of the reference
The measurement of source yield was made with a
fission chamber containing a 235U deposit. The
corrected fission count was related to the neutron
yield, neutron spectrum and fission cross section.
Relative yield measurements were made at the detector
distance of 2.6 m and angle of 0.5 deg. Absolute
yield measurement was made at 7 MeV deuteron energy
using 235U deposit of known isotopic composition.
Measurements were made at several distances and
angles varied from 3 deg to 5.5 deg.
